## PIPEDA — 10 Fair Information Principles

PIPEDA (Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act,
S.C. 2000, c. 5) is Canada's federal private-sector privacy law. Ten
principles structure compliance.

Authoritative reference: <https://www.priv.gc.ca/en/privacy-topics/privacy-laws-in-canada/the-personal-information-protection-and-electronic-documents-act-pipeda/p_principle/>
(Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada; accessed 2026-05-12).

### 1. Accountability

- **What it requires**: designate someone accountable for compliance;
  document policies; train staff; ensure subprocessors meet equivalent
  standards.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: name of accountable
  officer + their email + reporting chain]`. Policy docs in this
  directory. Subprocessor list at [`subprocessors.md`](subprocessors.md).
- **TBD (lawyer review)**: written privacy management program;
  subprocessor DPA exchange template; internal review cadence (annual is
  a common starting point).

### 2. Identifying Purposes

- **What it requires**: identify the purposes of collection at or before
  the time of collection.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: privacy policy (see
  [`privacy-policy.md`](privacy-policy.md)) lists purposes per data
  category. `[fill in: brief summary of your major data categories and
  their purposes — e.g., account, transactional, marketing, analytics]`.
- **TBD**: lawyer review of purpose statements; per-tenant or per-feature
  customization where collection scope varies.

### 3. Consent

- **What it requires**: knowledge + consent for collection, use, and
  disclosure (with limited exceptions in PIPEDA s. 7).
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: consent mechanism —
  e.g., signup flow check-box, intake form e-signature, opt-in modal]`;
  explicit opt-in for marketing email is separated from transactional
  consent (CASL requirement layered on top).
- **TBD**: granular consent UI for secondary uses; consent log retention
  policy; consent withdrawal mechanism reachable from the user account.

### 4. Limiting Collection

- **What it requires**: collect only what is necessary for the identified
  purposes.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: data-collection review
  practice — when forms are added or modified, who reviews the fields
  for necessity]`.
- **TBD**: periodic schema audit; "what we collect" review at every
  feature add.

### 5. Limiting Use, Disclosure, and Retention

- **What it requires**: use only for the identified purposes; retain
  only as long as needed; dispose of personal information in a secure
  manner.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: data retention policy `[fill in:
  link to or describe the project's retention rules per data class]`.
  No data sale; secondary uses (analytics, model training) are scoped to
  what was consented to.
- **TBD**: retention windows per data class (lawyer-confirmed);
  automated purge after retention expires.

### 6. Accuracy

- **What it requires**: keep personal information accurate, complete,
  and up-to-date as is necessary for the purposes.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: where users can edit
  their profile / submit corrections]`.
- **TBD**: process for individual-initiated correction requests routed
  to the right team; SLA for correction.

### 7. Safeguards

- **What it requires**: physical, organizational, and technological
  safeguards proportional to the sensitivity of the information.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: TLS in transit; encryption at rest
  (vendor default); database access controls; audit logging (see
  [`audit-log-requirements.md`](audit-log-requirements.md)); role-based
  access; secret-scanning hooks on commits.
  `[fill in: project-specific safeguards — RLS rules, IAM model, etc.]`.
- **TBD**: external penetration test cadence; tabletop incident
  exercise; vendor-incident escalation paths.

### 8. Openness

- **What it requires**: make policies and practices about the management
  of personal information readily available.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: privacy policy published at
  `[fill in: public URL]`. Subprocessor list available on request and
  published if/when the project ships SaaS.
- **TBD**: "policy version + last-updated" header on the public privacy
  policy; subprocessor-change notification mechanism for active
  customers.

### 9. Individual Access

- **What it requires**: on request, individuals can access their personal
  information and know how it has been used and disclosed.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: data-subject-access-
  request (DSAR) channel — email, in-app, or both — and the SLA the team
  commits to]`. PIPEDA's default response SLA is 30 days from receipt.
- **TBD**: DSAR runbook; right-to-deletion flow; format of the data
  export.

### 10. Challenging Compliance

- **What it requires**: a complaint pathway for individuals who believe
  the organization has not complied.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: contact `[fill in: privacy
  contact email — e.g., privacy@example.com]`. Escalation to the OPC
  via <https://www.priv.gc.ca/en/report-a-concern/file-a-formal-privacy-complaint/file-a-complaint-against-a-business/>.
- **TBD**: contact channel + escalation path documented in the public
  privacy policy.

## Lawyer-review checklist (before any external launch)

- [ ] Privacy policy reviewed for PIPEDA + provincial alignment.
- [ ] Terms of Service reviewed (data-ownership and account-termination
      data-export language).
- [ ] DPA template ready for customers who request one.
- [ ] CASL-compliant marketing-email opt-in flow reviewed.
- [ ] Right-to-access + right-to-deletion flows reviewed.
- [ ] Breach response runbook reviewed (see
      [`breach-response.md`](breach-response.md) — notification timing,
      OPC contact path, internal escalation).
- [ ] Subprocessor list reviewed (DPAs in place for vendors that touch
      personal information).
- [ ] Audit-log content reviewed against the requirements in
      [`audit-log-requirements.md`](audit-log-requirements.md).

